[4] Reproduction number for aedes mosquitoes
Date: October 2020
Source: Emerging Infectious Diseases journal [edited]
https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/26/10/19-0957_article


ref: Haider N, Vairo F, Ippolito G, Zumla A, Kock RA. Basic reproduction number of chikungunya virus transmitted by _Aedes_ mosquitoes. Emerg Infect Dis. 2020; 26(10): 2429-2431. doi: 10.3201/eid2610.190957
--------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
We estimated the weighted mean basic reproduction number (R0) of chikungunya virus based on outbreak size. R0 was 3.4 (95% CI 2.4-4.2) and varied for 2 primary chikungunya mosquito vectors: 4.1 (95% CI 1.5-6.6) for _Aedes aegypti_ and 2.8 (95% CI 1.8-3.8) for _Ae. albopictus_.

Conclusions
-----------
We found the overall mean R0 for CHIKV was 3.4 (95% CI 2.4-4.2). Our estimated R0 of 4.1 (95% CI 1.5-6.6) for _Ae. aegypti_ mosquitoes suggests CHIKV could spread rapidly and cause high disease incidence in urban areas, where this species thrives. Our estimated CHIKV R0 for _Ae. albopictus _mosquitoes of 2.8 (95% CI 1.5-6.6) was lower than for _Ae. aegypti_ mosquitoes. In rural areas, where _Ae. albopictus_ mosquitoes are more prevalent, sylvatic cycles, maintenance of biodiversity including natural mosquito populations, and presence of hosts other than humans might reduce the effects of an outbreak. Early interventions targeting aedes mosquitoes will be vital to controlling CHIKV outbreaks.

--
communicated by:
Roland Hübner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
Belgium
<roland.hubner@sante.belgique.be>

[One hopes that the current attempts to control _Aedes aegypti_ populations by genetic manipulation and release of sterile males and reduction of virus transmission efficiency by blockage of mid-gut infection with wolbachia bacteria can be applied successful over large areas with a reduction in transmission of chikungunya, dengue, and Zika viruses. - Mod.TY]

