[5] Mexico (Acapulco, Guerrero State): relapse, 2015
Date: Tue 29 Sep 2020
Source: Vector-Borne and Zoonotic Diseases journal [edited]
https://www.liebertpub.com/doi/10.1089/vbz.2020.2615


ref: de la Cruz-Castro IX, Nava-Aguilera E, Morales-Perez A, et al. Factors associated with chikungunya relapse in Acapulco, Mexico: A cross-sectional study. Vector Borne Zoonotic Dis. 2020 Oct; 20(10): 782-787. doi: 10.1089/vbz.2020.2615. Epub 17 Jun 2020. PMID: 32552425.
--------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Materials and methods
A cross-sectional study in December 2015 included 1305 homes in 8 urban clusters considered representative of Acapulco in southern Mexico. Administered questionnaires collated information on 5870 individuals, including sociodemographic variables, a history of chronic conditions, and the self-reporting of chikungunya. Bivariate and multivariate analyses relied on a cluster-adjusted Mantel-Haenszel procedure to identify the factors associated with chikungunya and its relapse.

Results
Some 66% (3531/5870) of the population reported suffering chikungunya and 31.1% (1098/3531) reported a relapse. Factors associated with relapse included the severity of the chikungunya case (odds ratio [OR]: 3.35; clusters adjusted 95% confidence interval [95% CIca]: 3.16-3.55); history of arthralgia (OR: 2.96; 95% CIca: 2.27-3.86); age 30 years or older (OR: 1.85; 95% CIca: 1.72-1.98); female (OR: 1.64; 95% CIca: 1.42-1.90); and higher education households (OR: 1.18; 95% CIca: 1.11-1.27).

Conclusions
The high occurrence of chikungunya and its relapse are a public health problem. The factors associated with relapse do not immediately suggest specific prevention strategies but emphasize the dire need for effective approaches to vector control.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In this study, relapse is defined as a reported recurrence of chikungunya symptoms (joint pain and inflammation) after 1 month having recovered from the disease. The chronic arthralgia following acute febrile chikungunya virus infection can persists for weeks to even years. This condition can be incapacitating making work and normal activities difficult to impossible. Unfortunately, there is no vaccine available to prevent infection so avoidance of mosquito bites and vector mosquito control are the only practical measures for prevention of infection. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED map of Mexico: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7948813,1666.]
